# Frontend Design Patterns (Guidelines)

Patterns are optional tools. Use only when they clearly improve clarity, reduce complexity, or improve maintainability.

---

## 1. Container / Presentational Pattern
Use when:
- logic and UI need clear separation
- components become too complex

Avoid when:
- component is simple and self-contained

---

## 2. Custom Hooks
Use when:
- logic is reused across components
- stateful or side-effect logic must be isolated

Avoid when:
- logic is local and simple

---

## 3. Adapter Pattern
Use when:
- external API data must be normalized
- API structure is unstable or inconsistent

Avoid when:
- API response is already stable and clean

---

## 4. Compound Components
Use when:
- building complex, composable UI systems (modals, dropdowns, tables)

Avoid when:
- UI is simple or static

---

## 5. Pattern Selection Rule
Prefer simplicity over abstraction.
Do not introduce patterns by default.
Apply patterns only when they clearly reduce complexity or duplication.